        <mxCell id="BoEJYoLPA0RRZZqsQ0T6-44" parent="1" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" value="REST API" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="70" x="1202.17" y="550" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="BoEJYoLPA0RRZZqsQ0T6-46" parent="1" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" value="HTTP GET" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="70" x="1140" y="620" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="BoEJYoLPA0RRZZqsQ0T6-47" parent="1" style="shape=note;strokeWidth=2;fontSize=13;size=20;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#fff2cc;strokeColor=#d6b656;fontColor=#666600;align=left;" value="&lt;div&gt;I chose Node-RED as the integration layer because it supports multiple protocols such as BACnet, Modbus RTU/TCP, MQTT, and API integration, while also allowing fast scenario-based simulation and payload preparation. I also have experience with Neuron, which is another strong industrial integration platform, but Node-RED was a better fit for this project because it offered a more flexible workflow within the assessment timeline.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;MQTT was selected as the telemetry transport protocol because it is lightweight, efficient, and well suited for real-time IoT data exchange using a publish/subscribe model.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;For the backend, I used Python with FastAPI because it allows fast and clean API development while keeping the code easy to understand and maintain.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;For storage, I used PostgreSQL because it is reliable and sufficient for telemetry history, latest values, and dashboard queries in a project of this scale. I did not use a dedicated time-series database here because it would add unnecessary complexity, but for larger production-scale systems with higher data volume and longer retention requirements, I would consider using a time-series database architecture.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;For the frontend, I used HTML and JavaScript to create a lightweight dashboard that is simple to run and suitable for demonstrating the required monitoring and visualization features.&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="260" width="960" x="70" y="670" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
      </root>
    </mxGraphModel>
